# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cocoa-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Cocoa consists of the Foundation Kit, Application Kit, and Core Data frameworks, as included by the `Cocoa.h` header file, and the libraries and frameworks included by those, such as the C standard library and the Objective-C runtime.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Cocoa applications are typically developed using the development tools provided by Apple, specifically Xcode (formerly Project Builder) and Interface Builder (now part of Xcode), using the programming languages Objective-C or Swift.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] However, the Cocoa programming environment can be accessed using other tools.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] It is also possible to write Objective-C Cocoa programs in a simple text editor and build it manually with GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) or Clang from the command line or from a makefile.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] For end users, Cocoa applications are those written using the Cocoa programming environment.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Such applications usually have a familiar look and feel, since the Cocoa programming environment provides a lot of common UI elements (such as buttons, scroll bars, etc.), and automates many aspects of an application to comply with Apple's human interface guidelines.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] For iOS, iPadOS, tvOS, and watchOS, APIs similar to Application Kit, named UIKit and WatchKit, are available; they include gesture recognition, animation, and a different set of graphical control elements that are designed to accommodate the specific platforms they target.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Foundation Kit and Core Data are also available in those operating systems.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] It is used in applications for Apple devices such as the iPhone, the iPod Touch, the iPad, the Apple TV, and the Apple Watch.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Cocoa continues the lineage of several software frameworks (mainly the *App Kit* and *Foundation Kit*) from the NeXTSTEP and OpenStep programming environments developed by NeXT in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Apple acquired NeXT in December 1996, and subsequently went to work on the Rhapsody operating system that was to be the direct successor of OPENSTEP.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] It was to have had an emulation base for classic Mac OS applications, named *Blue Box*.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] The OpenStep base of libraries and binary support was termed *Yellow Box*.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Rhapsody evolved into Mac OS X, and the Yellow Box became Cocoa.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Thus, Cocoa classes begin with the letters *NS*, such as NSString or NSArray.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] These stand for the original proprietary term for the OpenStep framework, NeXTSTEP.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Much of the work that went into developing OpenStep was applied to developing Mac OS X, Cocoa being the most visible part.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] For example, NeXTSTEP and OpenStep used Display PostScript for on-screen display of text and graphics, while Cocoa depends on Apple's Quartz (which uses the Portable Document Format (PDF) imaging model, but not its underlying technology).
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Cocoa also has a level of World Wide Web support, including the NSURL and WebKit HTML classes, and others, while OpenStep had only rudimentary support for managed network connections via NSFileHandle classes and Berkeley sockets.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] The API toolbox was originally called “Yellow Box” and was renamed to Cocoa - a name that had been already trademarked by Apple.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Apple's *Cocoa* trademark had originated as the name of a multimedia project design application for children.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] The name was intended to evoke "Java for kids", as it ran embedded in web pages.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] The original "Cocoa" program was discontinued following the return of Steve Jobs to Apple.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] At the time, Java was a big focus area for the company, so “Cocoa” was used as the new name for “Yellow Box” because, in addition to the native Objective-C usage, it could also be accessed from Java via a bridging layer.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Even though Apple discontinued support for the Cocoa Java bridge, the name continued and was even used for the Cocoa Touch API.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] One feature of the Cocoa environment is its facility for managing dynamically allocated memory.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Foundation Kit's NSObject class, from which most classes, both vendor and user, are derived, implements a reference counting scheme for memory management.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Objects that derive from the NSObject root class respond to a `retain` and a `release` message, and keep a retain count.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] A method titled `retainCount` exists, but contrary to its name, will usually not return the exact retain count of an object.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] It is mainly used for system-level purposes.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Invoking it manually is not recommended by Apple.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] A newly allocated object created with `alloc` or `copy` has a retain count of one.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Sending that object a `retain` message increments the retain count, while sending it a `release` message decrements the retain count.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] When an object's retain count reaches zero, it is deallocated by a procedure similar to a C++ *destructor*.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] `dealloc` is not guaranteed to be invoked.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Starting with Objective-C 2.0, the Objective-C runtime implemented an optional garbage collector, which is now obsolete and deprecated in favor of Automatic Reference Counting (ARC).
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] In this model, the runtime turned Cocoa reference counting operations such as "retain" and "release" into no-ops.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] The garbage collector does not exist on the iOS implementation of Objective-C 2.0.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Garbage collection in Objective-C ran on a low-priority background thread, and can halt on Cocoa's user events, with the intention of keeping the user experience responsive.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] The legacy garbage collector is still available on Mac OS X version 10.13, but no Apple-provided applications use it.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] In 2011, the LLVM compiler introduced Automatic Reference Counting (ARC), which replaces the conventional garbage collector by performing static analysis of Objective-C source code and inserting retain and release messages as necessary.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Cocoa consists of three Objective-C object libraries called *frameworks*.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Frameworks are functionally similar to shared libraries, a compiled object that can be dynamically loaded into a program's address space at runtime, but frameworks add associated resources, header files, and documentation.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] The Cocoa frameworks are implemented as a type of bundle, containing the aforementioned items in standard locations.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] A key part of the Cocoa architecture is its comprehensive views model.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] This is organized along conventional lines for an application framework, but is based on the Portable Document Format (PDF) drawing model provided by Quartz.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] This allows creating custom drawing content using PostScript-like drawing commands, which also allows automatic printer support and so forth.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Since the Cocoa framework manages all the clipping, scrolling, scaling and other chores of drawing graphics, the programmer is freed from implementing basic infrastructure and can concentrate on the unique aspects of an application's content.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] The Smalltalk teams at Xerox PARC eventually settled on a design philosophy that led to easy development and high code reuse.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Cocoa's design is a fairly, but not absolutely strict application of MVC principles.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Under OpenStep, most of the classes provided were either high-level View classes (in AppKit) or one of a number of relatively low-level model classes like NSString.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Compared to similar MVC systems, OpenStep lacked a strong model layer.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] No stock class represented a "document," for instance.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] During the transition to Cocoa, the model layer was expanded greatly, introducing a number of pre-rolled classes to provide functionality common to desktop applications.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] In Mac OS X 10.3, Apple introduced the NSController family of classes, which provide predefined behavior for the controller layer.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] These classes are considered part of the Cocoa Bindings system, which also makes extensive use of protocols such as Key-Value Observing and Key-Value Binding.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] The term 'binding' refers to a relationship between two objects, often between a view and a controller.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Bindings allow the developer to focus more on declarative relationships rather than orchestrating fine-grained behavior.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] With the arrival of Mac OS X 10.4, Apple extended this foundation further by introducing the Core Data framework, which standardizes change tracking and persistence in the model layer.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] In effect, the framework greatly simplifies the process of making changes to application data, undoing changes when necessary, saving data to disk, and reading it back in.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] In providing framework support for all three MVC domains, Apple's goal is to reduce the amount of boilerplate or "glue" code that developers have to write, freeing up resources to spend time on application-specific features.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] In most object-oriented languages, calls to methods are represented physically by a pointer to the code in memory.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] This restricts the design of an application since specific *command handling* classes are needed, usually organized according to the chain-of-responsibility pattern.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] While Cocoa retains this approach for the most part, Objective-C's late binding opens up more flexibility.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Under Objective-C, methods are represented by a *selector*, a string describing the method to call.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] When a message is sent, the selector is sent into the Objective-C runtime, matched against a list of available methods, and the method's *implementation* is called.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Since the selector is text data, this lets it be saved to a file, transmitted over a network or between processes, or manipulated in other ways.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] The implementation of the method is looked up at runtime, not compile time.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] There is a small performance penalty for this, but late binding allows the same selector to reference different implementations.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] By a similar token, Cocoa provides a pervasive data manipulation method called *key-value coding* (KVC).
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] This allows a piece of data or property of an object to be looked up or changed at runtime by name.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] The property name acts as a key to the value.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] In traditional languages, this late binding is impossible.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] An object's type need not be known, yet any property of that object can be discovered using KVC.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Also, by extending this system using something Cocoa terms *key-value observing* (KVO), automatic support for undo-redo is provided.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Late static binding is a variant of binding somewhere between static and dynamic binding.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] The binding of names before the program is run is called static (*early*); bindings performed as the program runs are dynamic (*late* or *virtual*).
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] One of the most useful features of Cocoa is the powerful *base objects* the system supplies.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] As an example, consider the Foundation classes `NSString` and `NSAttributedString`, which provide Unicode strings, and the `NSText` system in AppKit, which allows the programmer to place string objects in the GUI.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] `NSText` and its related classes are used to display and edit strings.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Paragraph layout can be controlled automatically or by the user, using a built-in "ruler" object that can be attached to any text view.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Spell checking is automatic, using a system-wide set of language dictionaries.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Unlimited undo/redo support is built in.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Using only the built-in features, one can write a text editor application in as few as 10 lines of code.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] With new controller objects, this may fall towards zero.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] When extensions are needed, Cocoa's use of Objective-C makes this a straightforward task.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Objective-C includes the concept of "categories," which allows modifying existing class "in-place".
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Functionality can be accomplished in a category without any changes to the original classes in the framework, or even access to its source.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] In other common languages, this same task requires deriving a new subclass supporting the added features, and then replacing all instances of the original class with instances of the new subclass.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] The Cocoa frameworks are written in Objective-C.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Cocoa's need for runtime binding means many of Cocoa's key features are not available with Java.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] In 2005, Apple announced that the Java bridge was to be deprecated, meaning that features added to Cocoa in macOS versions later than 10.4 would not be added to the Cocoa-Java programming interface.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] At Apple Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) 2014, Apple introduced a new programming language named Swift, which is intended to replace Objective-C.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Originally, AppleScript Studio could be used to develop simpler Cocoa applications.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] However, as of Snow Leopard, it has been deprecated.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] It was replaced with AppleScriptObjC, which allows programming in AppleScript, while using Cocoa frameworks.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] The Cocoa programming environment can be accessed using other tools with the aid of bridge mechanisms such as PasCocoa, PyObjC, CamelBones, RubyCocoa, and a D/Objective-C Bridge.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] Third-party bindings available for other languages include AppleScript, Clozure CL, Monobjc and NObjective (C#), Cocoa# (CLI), Cocodao and D/Objective-C Bridge, LispWorks, Object Pascal, CamelBones (Perl), PyObjC (Python), FPC PasCocoa (Lazarus and Free Pascal), RubyCocoa (Ruby).
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] A Ruby language implementation named MacRuby, which removes the need for a bridge mechanism, was formerly developed by Apple, while Nu is a Lisp-like language that uses the Objective-C object model directly, and thus can use the Cocoa frameworks without needing a binding.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-api] There are also open source implementations of major parts of the Cocoa framework, such as GNUstep and Cocotron, which allow cross-platform Cocoa application development to target other operating systems, such as Microsoft Windows and Linux.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-touch] UIKit provides an abstraction layer of iOS, the operating system for the iPhone, iPod Touch, and iPad.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-touch] UIKit is similar to AppKit from the macOS Cocoa API toolset, and it too is primarily written in the Objective-C language.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-touch] UIKit allows the use of hardware and features that are not found in macOS computers and are thus unique to the iOS range of devices.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-touch] Like AppKit, UIKit follows a Model–View–Controller (MVC) software architecture.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-touch] UIKit contains a different set of graphical control elements from AppKit.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-touch] Tools for developing applications based on UIKit are included in the iOS SDK.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-touch] iOS, watchOS, and tvOS technologies can be seen as a set of layers, with UIKit at the highest level and the core operating system / kernel at the bottom.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-touch] UIKit provides the key frameworks for developing applications on devices running iOS, and is based atop Foundation Kit.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-touch] Microsoft's WinObjC, the GNUstep-based iOS bridge for the Universal Windows Platform, contains working implementations of frameworks such as Foundation, UIKit, and MapKit released under the MIT License.
[src:cocoa-framework/cocoa-touch] One of the UIKit implementations is based on XAML.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] The most prevalent use of Core Foundation is for passing its own primitive types for data, including raw bytes, Unicode strings, numbers, calendar dates, and UUIDs, as well as collections such as arrays, sets, and dictionaries, to numerous macOS C routines, primarily those that are GUI-related.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] Other parts of the API include utility routines and wrappers around existing APIs for ease of use.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] Utility routines perform such actions as file system and network I/O through `CFReadStream`, `CFWriteStream`, and `CFURL` and endianness translation (Byte Order Utilities).
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] Some examples of wrapper routines include those for Core Foundation's wrapper routines for Unix sockets, the CFSocket API.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] Some types in Core Foundation are "toll-free bridged", or interchangeable with a simple cast, with those of their Foundation Kit counterparts.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] For example, one could create a `CFDictionaryRef` Core Foundation type, and then later simply use a standard C cast to convert it to its Objective-C counterpart, `NSDictionary *`, and then use the desired Objective-C methods on that object as one normally would.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] Core Foundation has a plug-in model (CFPlugin) that is based on the Microsoft Component Object Model.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] Apple used to release most of CF as an open-source project called CFLite that can be used to write cross-platform applications for macOS, Linux, and Windows.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] A third-party open-source implementation called OpenCFLite extends the Apple CFLite for building on 32-bit Windows and Linux environments.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] It is maintained by one of the WebKit developers, but was stalled by 2015.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] The karaoke platform KJams maintains a fork since 2017.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] This version, by its programmer David M.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] Cotter, supports 64-bit systems and has a CFNetwork implementation with LibreSSL-based TLS.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] A fork of OpenCFLite was created by Grant Erickson (an original collaborator with Brent Fulgham on the SourceForge version) in 2021 with a companion port of the `CFHost` portion of CFNetwork, as OpenCFNetwork.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] The Swift Corelib Foundation, a fallback version of the Foundation Kit for the Swift programming language for non-Apple platforms, contains a near-full version of the Core Foundation released under Apache License 2.0.
[src:cocoa-framework/core-foundation] GNUstep includes a version of the Core Foundation called "libs-corebase".
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] Interface Builder is descended from the NeXTSTEP development software of the same name.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] A version of Interface Builder is also used in the development of OpenStep software, and a very similar tool called Gorm exists for GNUstep.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] On March 27, 2008, a specialized iPhone version of Interface Builder allowing interface construction for iPhone applications was released with the iPhone SDK Beta 2.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] Interface Builder was intentionally developed as a separate application, to allow interaction designers to design interfaces without having to use a code-oriented IDE, but as of Xcode 4, Apple has integrated its functionality directly into Xcode.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] Originally the software was called *SOS Interface*, and was created by Jean-Marie Hullot whilst he was a researcher at Inria at Rocquencourt near Paris.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] He was allowed to retain ownership of the software upon resigning from Inria, and spent a year working it into a fully-featured product, now named *Interface Builder* and distributed for Macintosh by ExperTelligence in the USA in 1986.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] It was written in Lisp (for the *ExperLisp* product by *ExperTelligence*) and deeply integrated with the Macintosh Toolbox.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] *Interface Builder* was presented at MacWorld Expo in San Francisco in January 1987.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] Denison Bollay took Jean-Marie Hullot to NeXT after MacWorld Expo to demonstrate it to Steve Jobs.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] Jobs recognized its value, and started incorporating it into NeXTSTEP, and by 1988 it was part of NeXTSTEP 0.8.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] It was the first commercial application that allowed interface objects, such as buttons, menus, and windows, to be placed in an interface using a mouse.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] One notable early use of *Interface Builder* was the development of the first web browser, WorldWideWeb by Tim Berners-Lee at CERN, made using a NeXT workstation.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] Interface Builder provides *palettes*, or collections, of user interface objects to an Objective-C or Swift developer.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] These user interface objects contain items like text fields, data tables, sliders, and pop-up menus.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] Interface Builder's palettes are completely extensible, meaning any developer can develop new objects and add palettes to Interface Builder.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] To build an interface, a developer simply drags interface objects from the palette onto a window or menu.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] *Actions* (messages) which the objects can emit are connected to *targets* in the application's code and *outlets* (pointers) declared in the application's code are connected to specific objects.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] In this way all initialization is done before runtime, both improving performance and streamlining the development process.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] When Interface Builder was a standalone application, interface designers could ship nib files to developers, who would then drop them into their projects.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] Interface Builder saves an application's interface as a bundle that contains the interface objects and relationships used in the application.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] These objects are archived (a process also known as serialization or marshalling in other contexts) into either an XML file or a NeXT-style property list file with a .nib extension.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] Upon running an application, the proper NIB objects are unarchived, connected into the binary of their owning application, and awakened.
[src:cocoa-framework/interface-builder] As of Interface Builder version 3, a new file format (with extension .xib) has been added, which is functionally identical to .nib, except it is stored in a flat file, making it more suitable for storage in revision control systems and processing by tools such as diff.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:cocoa-framework/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Objective-C programs developed for non-Apple operating systems or that are not dependent on Apple's APIs may also be compiled for any platform supported by GNU, GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) or LLVM/Clang.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Objective-C source code "messaging/implementation" program files usually have `.m` filename extensions, while Objective-C "header/interface" files have `.h` extensions, the same as C header files.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Objective-C++ files are denoted with a `.mm` filename extension.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Objective-C was created mainly by Brad Cox and Tom Love in the early 1980s at their company Productivity Products International (PPI).
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Leading up to the creation of their company, both had been introduced to Smalltalk while at ITT Corporation's Programming Technology Center in 1981.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The earliest work on Objective-C traces back to around then.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Cox was intrigued by problems of true reusability in software design and programming.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] He realized that a language like Smalltalk would be invaluable in building development environments for system developers at ITT.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] However, he and Tom Love also recognized that backward compatibility with C was critically important in ITT's telecom engineering milieu.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Cox began writing a pre-processor for C to add some of the abilities of Smalltalk.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] He soon had a working implementation of an object-oriented extension to the C language, which he named Object-Oriented Pre-Compiler (OOPC).
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Love was hired by Schlumberger Research in 1982 and had the opportunity to acquire the first commercial copy of Smalltalk-80, which further influenced the development of their brainchild.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] To demonstrate that real progress could be made, Cox showed that making interchangeable software components really needed only a few practical changes to existing tools.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Specifically, they needed to support objects in a flexible manner, come supplied with a usable set of libraries, and allow for the code (and any resources needed by the code) to be bundled into one cross-platform format.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Love and Cox eventually formed PPI to commercialize their product.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] To avoid legal disputes with his previous employers, Cox reimplemented his compiler for the language, which was renamed "Objective-C".
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The company's main product line consisted of this compiler, along with class libraries intended to be used with it.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In 1986, Cox published the main description of Objective-C in its original form in the book *Object-Oriented Programming: An Evolutionary Approach*.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Although he was careful to explain that there is more to the problem of reusability than just what Objective-C provides, the language was often compared feature for feature with other languages.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In 1988, NeXT licensed Objective-C from StepStone (the new name of PPI, the owner of the Objective-C trademark) and extended the GCC compiler to support Objective-C.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] NeXT developed the Application Kit (AppKit) and Foundation Kit libraries on which the NeXTSTEP user interface and Interface Builder were based.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] While the NeXT workstations failed to make a great impact in the marketplace, the tools were widely lauded in the industry.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] NeXT dropped hardware production and focused on software tools, selling NeXTSTEP (and OPENSTEP) as a platform for custom programming.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] To circumvent the terms of the GPL, NeXT had originally intended to ship the Objective-C frontend separately, allowing the user to link it with GCC to produce the compiler executable.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Stallman, this plan was rejected after Stallman consulted with GNU's lawyers and NeXT agreed to make Objective-C part of GCC.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The work to extend GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) was led by Steve Naroff, who joined NeXT from StepStone.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The compiler changes were made available as per GNU General Public License (GPL) terms, but the runtime libraries were not, rendering the open source contribution unusable to the general public.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] This led to other parties developing such runtime libraries under open source licenses.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Later, Steve Naroff was also principal contributor to work at Apple to build the Objective-C frontend to Clang.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The GNU project started work on its free software implementation of Cocoa, named GNUstep, based on the OpenStep standard.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Dennis Glatting wrote the first GNU Objective-C runtime in 1992.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The current GNU Objective-C runtime, in use since 1993, is the one developed by Kresten Krab Thorup while he was a university student in Denmark.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Thorup also worked at NeXT from 1993 to 1996.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] After acquiring NeXT in 1996, Apple Computer used OpenStep in its then-new operating system, Mac OS X.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] This included Objective-C, NeXT's Objective-C-based developer tool, Project Builder, and its interface design tool, Interface Builder.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Both were later merged into one application, Xcode.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Most of Apple's current Cocoa API is based on OpenStep interface objects and is the most significant Objective-C environment being used for active development.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] At Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) 2014, Apple introduced a new language, Swift, which was characterized as "Objective-C without the C".
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Objective-C is a thin layer atop C and is a "strict superset" of C, meaning that it is possible to compile any C program with an Objective-C compiler and to freely include C language code within an Objective-C class.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Objective-C derives its object syntax from Smalltalk.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] All of the syntax for non-object-oriented operations (including primitive variables, pre-processing, expressions, function declarations, and function calls) are identical to those of C, while the syntax for object-oriented features is an implementation of Smalltalk-style messaging.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The Objective-C model of object-oriented programming is based on message passing to object instances.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In Objective-C, one does not *call a method*; one *sends a message*.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] This is unlike the Simula-style programming model used by C++.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The difference between these two concepts is in how the code referenced by the method or message name is executed.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In a Simula-style language, the method name is—in most cases—bound to a section of code in the target class by the compiler.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In Smalltalk and Objective-C, the target of a message is resolved at runtime, with the receiving object itself interpreting the message.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] A method is identified by a *selector* or `SEL` — a unique identifier for each message name, often just a `NUL`-terminated string representing its name—and resolved to a C method pointer implementing it: an `IMP`.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] A consequence of this is that the message-passing system has no type checking.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The object to which the message is directed—the *receiver*—is not guaranteed to respond to a message, and if it does not, it raises an exception.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The "method" call is translated by the compiler to the `objc_msgSend(id self, SEL op, ...)` family of runtime functions.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Different implementations handle modern additions like `super`.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In GNU families, this function is named `objc_msg_sendv`, but it has been deprecated in favor of a modern lookup system under `objc_msg_lookup`.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Both styles of programming have multiple strengths and weaknesses.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Object-oriented programming in the Simula (C++) style allows multiple inheritance and faster execution by using compile-time binding whenever possible, but it does not support dynamic binding by default.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] It also forces all methods to have a corresponding implementation unless they are abstract.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The Smalltalk-style programming as used in Objective-C allows messages to go unimplemented, with the method resolved to its implementation at runtime.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] For example, a message may be sent to a collection of objects, to which only some will be expected to respond, without fear of producing runtime errors.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Message passing also does not require that an object be defined at compile time.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] An implementation is still required for the method to be called in the derived object.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Objective-C requires that the interface and implementation of a class be in separately declared code blocks.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] By convention, developers place the interface in a header file and the implementation in a code file.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The header files, normally suffixed .h, are similar to C header files while the implementation (method) files, normally suffixed .m, can be very similar to C code files.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] This is analogous to class declarations as used in other object-oriented languages, such as C++ or Python.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The interface of a class is usually defined in a header file.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] A common convention is to name the header file after the name of the class, e.g.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] `Ball.h` would contain the interface for the class `Ball`.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In the above, plus signs denote class methods, or methods that can be called on the class itself (not on an instance), and minus signs denote instance methods, which can only be called on a particular instance of the class.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Class methods also have no access to instance variables.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Note that `instanceMethod2With2Parameters:param2_callName:` demonstrates the interleaving of selector segments with argument expressions, for which there is no direct equivalent in C/C++.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Return types can be any standard C type, a pointer to a generic Objective-C object, a pointer to a specific type of object such as NSArray *, NSImage *, or NSString *, or a pointer to the class to which the method belongs (instancetype).
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The default return type is the generic Objective-C type `id`.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Method arguments begin with a name labeling the argument that is part of the method name, followed by a colon followed by the expected argument type in parentheses and the argument name.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] A derivative of the interface definition is the *category*, which allows one to add methods to existing classes.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The interface only declares the class interface and not the methods themselves: the actual code is written in the implementation file.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Implementation (method) files normally have the file extension `.m`, which originally signified "messages".
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Methods are written using their interface declarations.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The syntax allows pseudo-naming of arguments.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Internal representations of a method vary between different implementations of Objective-C.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] If myColor is of the class `Color`, instance method `-changeColorToRed:green:blue:` might be internally labeled `_i_Color_changeColorToRed_green_blue`.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The `i` is to refer to an instance method, with the class and then method names appended and colons changed to underscores.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] As the order of parameters is part of the method name, it cannot be changed to suit coding style or expression as with true named parameters.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] However, internal names of the function are rarely used directly.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Generally, messages are converted to function calls defined in the Objective-C runtime library.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] It is not necessarily known at link time which method will be called because the class of the receiver (the object being sent the message) need not be known until runtime.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Once an Objective-C class is written, it can be instantiated.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] This is done by first allocating an uninitialized instance of the class (an object) and then by initializing it.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] An object is not fully functional until both steps have been completed.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] These steps should be accomplished with one line of code so that there is never an allocated object that hasn't undergone initialization (and because it is unwise to keep the intermediate result since `-init` can return a different object than that on which it is called).
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Also, some classes implement class method initializers.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Like `+new`, they combine `+alloc` and `-init`, but unlike `+new`, they return an autoreleased instance.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The *alloc* message allocates enough memory to hold all the instance variables for an object, sets all the instance variables to zero values, and turns the memory into an instance of the class; at no point during the initialization is the memory an instance of the superclass.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The *init* message performs the set-up of the instance upon creation.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In the above example, notice the `id` return type.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] This type stands for *pointer to any object* in Objective-C (See the Dynamic typing section).
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The initializer pattern is used to assure that the object is properly initialized by its superclass before the init method performs its initialization.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] A non-valid object pointer has the value `nil`; conditional statements like `if` treat nil like a null pointer, so the initialization code will not be executed if `[super init]` returned nil.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] If there is an error in initialization, the init method should perform any necessary cleanup, including sending a `release` message to self, and return `nil` to indicate that initialization failed.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Any checking for such errors must only be performed after having called the superclass initialization to ensure that destroying the object will be done correctly.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] If a class has more than one initialization method, only one of them (the *designated initializer*) needs to follow this pattern; others should call the designated initializer instead of the superclass initializer.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In other programming languages, these are called *interfaces*.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Objective-C was extended at NeXT to introduce the concept of multiple inheritance of specification, but not implementation, through the introduction of protocols.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] This is a pattern achievable either as an abstract multiple inherited base class in C++, or as an *interface* (as in Java and C#).
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Objective-C makes use of ad hoc protocols called *informal protocols* and compiler-enforced protocols called *formal protocols*.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] An informal protocol is a list of methods that a class can opt to implement.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] It is specified in the documentation, since it has no presence in the language.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Informal protocols are implemented as a category (see below) on NSObject and often include optional methods, which, if implemented, can change the behavior of a class.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] For example, a text field class might have a delegate that implements an informal protocol with an optional method for performing auto-completion of user-typed text.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The text field discovers whether the delegate implements that method (via reflective programming (reflection)) and, if so, calls the delegate's method to support the auto-complete feature.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] A formal protocol is similar to an interface in Java, C#, and Ada 2005.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] It is a list of methods that any class can declare itself to implement.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Objective-C versions before 2.0 required that a class must implement all methods in a protocol it declares itself as adopting; the compiler will emit an error if the class does not implement every method from its declared protocols.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Objective-C 2.0 added support for marking certain methods in a protocol optional, and the compiler will not enforce implementation of optional methods.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] A class must be declared to implement that protocol to be said to conform to it.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Formal protocols cannot provide any implementations; they simply assure callers that classes that conform to the protocol will provide implementations.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In the NeXT/Apple library, protocols are frequently used by the Distributed Objects system to represent the abilities of an object executing on a remote system.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] denotes that there is the abstract idea of locking.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] instances of NSLock claim that they will provide an implementation for the two instance methods.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Objective-C, like Smalltalk, can use dynamic typing: an object can be sent a message that is not specified in its interface.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] This can allow for increased flexibility, as it allows an object to "capture" a message and send the message to a different object that can respond to the message appropriately, or likewise send the message on to another object.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] This behavior is known as *message forwarding* or *delegation* (see below).
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Alternatively, an error handler can be used in case the message cannot be forwarded.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] If an object does not forward a message, respond to it, or handle an error, then the system will generate a runtime exception.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] If messages are sent to *nil* (the null object pointer), they will be silently ignored or raise a generic exception, depending on compiler options.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Static typing information may also optionally be added to variables.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] This information is then checked at compile time.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In the following four statements, increasingly specific type information is provided.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The statements are equivalent at runtime, but the extra information allows the compiler to warn the programmer if the passed argument does not match the type specified.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* may be of any class.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* may be an instance of any class that conforms to the *`NSCopying`* protocol.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* must be an instance of the *NSNumber* class.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* must be an instance of the *NSNumber* class, and it must conform to the *`NSCopying`* protocol.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] In Objective-C, all objects are represented as pointers, and static initialization is not allowed.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The simplest object is the type that id (objc_obj *) points to, which only has an *isa* pointer describing its class.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Other types from C, like values and structs, are unchanged because they are not part of the object system.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] This decision differs from the C++ object model, where structs and classes are united.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Objective-C permits the sending of a message to an object that may not respond.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Rather than responding or simply dropping the message, an object can forward the message to an object that can respond.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Forwarding can be used to simplify implementation of certain design patterns, such as the observer pattern or the proxy pattern.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] An object wishing to implement forwarding needs only to override the forwarding method with a new method to define the forwarding behavior.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The action method `performv::` need not be overridden, as this method merely performs an action based on the selector and arguments.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Notice the `SEL` type, which is the type of messages in Objective-C.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Note: in OpenStep, Cocoa, and GNUstep, the commonly used frameworks of Objective-C, one does not use the `Object` class.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] The `- (void)forwardInvocation:(NSInvocation *)anInvocation` method of the `NSObject` class is used to do forwarding.
[src:cocoa-framework/objective-c] Here is an example of a program that demonstrates the basics of forwarding.
